    thinking: "**Analyzing the Structure**\n\nOkay, so I\'m noticing a `\"type\": \"module\"` declaration, paired with a Vite dev server configuration. I see `express` and its type definitions listed in the dependencies. This setup is clearly hinting at a full-stack application structure, and I\'m quite intrigued by the possibilities.\n\n\n**Clarifying the Architecture**\n\nOkay, so I\'m thinking about how the Vite setup integrates with potential server-side operations. I\'m focusing on how the \"dev\" script and Vite\'s role might work alongside an Express server, considering options like middleware integration. I am also investigating how a standard Vite + Express full-stack architecture could be implemented. This requires an understanding of how the production start command is implemented in this platform and it\'s constraints.\n\n\n**Defining the Full-Stack**\n\nRight, so I\'m now certain about the server-side structure. I\'ve realized we can build a custom full-stack server using `server.ts`! I\'m planning to use Vite middleware for development, ensuring Hot Module Replacement and compilation. In production, serving static files from `dist/` is the plan. We can expose `/api/*` endpoints for backend logic using Express, ensuring full API functionality.\n\n\n**Implementing the `server.ts`**\n\nNow, I\'m fully confident in my design for `server.ts`! I\'m planning a robust Express setup. API keys will remain securely on the server-side, for optimal security and reliability. I\'ve got a great setup for both development and production. The API endpoint `/api/evaluate` will be the focal point, utilizing the Gemini API to the fullest extent. This promises a smooth transition for both.\n\n\n**Simplifying the Implementation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a simpler setup. By utilizing Vite middleware, I\'m confident that a robust full-stack implementation is totally achievable. I am now exploring potential streamlined structures. I\'m eager to dive into this approach. It looks like it is totally viable.\n\n\n**Reconsidering the Approach**\n\nI\'m now back at the `vite.config.ts`. I was just about to explore Vite\'s built-in proxy to route `/api/*` to an Express server. However, I\'ve hit a snag. The environment has a hardcoded port constraint, making my proxy idea problematic. It looks like I need a different strategy.\n\n\n**Refining the Server**\n\nOkay, the port constraint really shaped my approach. I\'ve realized Express must handle port 3000, and Vite becomes middleware within that same server. It\'s elegant! All requests hit 3000, eliminating separate development/production ports and enabling HMR. Production seamlessly serves `dist/` from Express. It is all so perfectly consistent. Now, it is time to write that perfect `server.ts`. I should probably check the design HTML. There\'s a request to apply the \"Editorial Aesthetic\" design, so let\'s start with colors and styling.\n\n\n**Defining the Editorial Aesthetic**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a solid aesthetic plan! The core colors will be a warm off-white background, charcoal text, and a muted gold accent. I\'m thinking soft gray-beige borders and a neutral background. For highlights, white text on charcoal. I\'ll use serif italic for headers, sans-serif for the UI, and mono for scores. I\'m planning clean spacing, elegant borders, and a beautiful card structure for the layout.\n\n\\n\\n\n\n**Structuring the UI**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on the user interface. I\'m setting up input layers for user submissions, considering text input and file uploads. I\'m making sure it supports IELTS Writing Task 1 & 2. I should also include the support for IELTS Speaking responses.\n\n\n**Expanding the Interface**\n\nI am now expanding the interface to incorporate IELTS speaking practice! I\'ll allow audio file uploads, transcript pasting, and a built-in voice recorder. I will also incorporate an analytics layer to assess submissions against the official IELTS scoring rubrics: Task Achievement, Coherence & Cohesion, Lexical Resource, and Grammatical Range & Accuracy. I\'ll include an overall band score with the correct rounding logic. I\'ll provide detailed analysis for each metric with the machine-readable JSON data output.\n\n\n**Designing the JSON Output**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the output format. I\'m focusing on crafting a JSON structure that includes a detailed correction matrix with error explanations and band score mapping. I\'m prioritizing high-impact suggestions for improvement across key IELTS metrics, alongside essential metadata. I\'m considering a React state manager to handle user submissions and feedback, exploring `localStorage` for now. However, I should consider durable cloud persistence for persistent storage.\n\n\n**Evaluating Persistence Needs**\n\nI\'m now thinking about data persistence. I see that the app focuses on auditing and immediate feedback, suggesting local storage. I\'ll utilize `localStorage` to create a history of reports. Furthermore, I will create utilities for saving beautiful JSON, or copying it, printing it or creating a PDF. It seems likely I will have to examine the `index.html` file, and `src/App.tsx`. I should check for any configuration files as well.\n\n\n**Structuring the Execution**\n\nOkay, I\'m now structuring the backend execution! I\'m planning the architecture for `server.ts`. I want to ensure API endpoint handling, and that I can serve Vite assets. I\'m checking the `package.json` scripts and realizing the `dev` script can be modified to run `server.ts`. Also, I\'m wondering if `node server.ts` directly will work in production, since Node 22+ natively supports TypeScript. I\'ll focus on getting the Express server code down first.\n\n\n**Verifying the Execution**\n\nI\'m now certain about running the server! Node.js natively runs TypeScript, which is fantastic. The `package.json`\'s `\"start\": \"node server.ts\"` setup is spot-on for our environment. I\'ve reconfirmed the Gemini API initialization method, including that crucial `\"User-Agent\"` header for authentication.\n\n\n**Defining the Prompt**\n\nI\'m now crafting the Gemini prompt for IELTS assessment! I will specify that it acts as a senior examiner and provide a JSON response structure. I am setting the format for `writing` or `speaking`, and then will specify `task1`, `task2`, `part1`, `part2`, or `part3`. Then I will specify the prompt/topic, and the submission text. The JSON response must include band scores, an overall band, and detailed feedback for each metric.\n\n\n**Refining the Output**\n\nI\'m now implementing the rounding logic for the overall band score! I\'ll properly implement the IELTS rounding rules, specifically handling the `.25` up to the next half-band case. I\'ll make sure it\'s accurate! I\'m now also focused on fine-tuning the JSON structure to include the official rounding rules and ensuring it\'s comprehensive and user-friendly. I\'m focusing on those corrections.\n\n\n**Calculating the Rounding**\n\nI\'m now writing and testing a TypeScript function to ensure correct IELTS band score rounding, which handles all cases per the rules! I\'ll build it for the server and frontend. I can also double-check the LLM\'s average against my calculated one for absolute certainty.\n\n\n**Verifying the Rounding**\n\nI\'ve tested the IELTS band score rounding function and confirmed it adheres to official rules! I\'ve covered all edge cases in my testing. I\'m satisfied that this is correct. I am ready to implement this in both the server-side and frontend now, ensuring perfect compliance with IELTS standards. I can finally see that server.ts is the path forward.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 42
      nanos: 862691376
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
