  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Microphone Usage**\n\nI\'ve decided to incorporate an in-app speech recorder for practicing Speaking tasks. The plan involves requesting `\"microphone\"` in `requestFramePermissions`. I anticipate this being a cool, premium, and functional addition to the app.\n\n\n**Analyzing App Structure**\n\nI\'m now diving into `/src/App.tsx`, which, surprisingly, is currently empty. My plan is to craft a complete React application within this file. The structure will feature tabs: \"New Evaluation,\" \"History & Reports,\" and an \"IELTS Scoring Guide.\" I\'m also considering evaluation options for \"Writing\" and \"Speaking\" practice, with task-specific choices and a topic/prompt area. I\'m focusing on a clean, functional design.\n\n\n**Implementing Speech Recognition**\n\nI\'m now focusing on incorporating the Web Speech API (`webkitSpeechRecognition`) for live voice recording. I\'ll provide an option for users to transcribe their speech using this native browser feature, directly in the \"Speaking\" section. This will eliminate the need for external APIs or offline transcription. The plan is to capture recordings, track time, and allow users to trigger an evaluation post-transcription. I\'m exploring the integration of this API, now.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Speech Transcription**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the \"Record & Transcribe\" functionality. It\'s a game-changer! The focus is on implementing real-time transcription using the Web Speech API. My priority is seamless fallback solutions if the API isn\'t available. I\'m aiming for high-quality, zero-cost speech-to-text integration, which I believe is a true premium feature that will be an incredible enhancement to the app.\n\n\n**Designing Evaluation Displays**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the user interface for evaluation results. My key focus is presenting feedback in a stunning, visual, and intuitive manner. I\'m prioritizing custom visualizations, specifically considering SVG radar/spider-web charts or a custom bar chart. The goal is to create a dynamic visual representation of the IELTS profile that is beautiful and matches the app\'s editorial aesthetic. I plan to incorporate an interactive correction matrix with live highlighting of corrected text within the essay display.\n\n\n**Refining Evaluation Reports**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing the data output and report generation. I\'m aiming for a clear bento layout that showcases strengths, weaknesses, and actionable advice in numbered lists. The plan includes an \"Export Report\" button for the full JSON data and a \"Generate Report\" print button that produces a browser-print-styled academic feedback document, matching the editorial aesthetic. Also, I\'m setting up default sample IELTS prompts and essays to facilitate instant app testing.\n\n\n**Reviewing UI Design**\n\nI\'m now deep into the UI details, especially the design language provided via the user\'s HTML. I\'m focusing on incorporating serif fonts for titles, as well as the correct header style, and the overall grid/flex layout and spacing. I\'m also preparing for the distinct column layout, including the right column correction matrix. I am ready to implement the `src/App.tsx` file.\n\n\n\n**Adapting Responsiveness**\n\nI\'m now integrating responsive design into `/src/App.tsx`, focusing on adapting to various screen sizes. I\'ll make the app\'s visual structure fluid, ensuring it maintains its proportions and style on both desktop and mobile. I will use the \"bento grid\" layout for desktop screens and a stacked layout for tablets and phones, ensuring it is visually appealing, elegant, and type-safe.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
